Tutorial

Login Application (NodeJS)

15 steps

In today's fast-paced digital landscape, user authentication stands as a cornerstone of trust, security, and accessibility in the online world. It is the vital mechanism that ensures that only authorized users can access the privileged areas and data of web applications, websites, and mobile applications.

Whether you've ever logged into a social media platform, checked your email, or shopped online, you've encountered user authentication in various forms, ranging from the familiar username-password combination to the more advanced two-factor authentication methods. It's the guardian of personal information, confidential data, and the integrity of digital interactions.

We will embark on a journey to create a robust and secure user authentication system. Our application will enable users to create their own accounts and subsequently log in with the same credentials. We'll harness the power of MongoDB to store user data securely.
Join us on Discord

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to

  • Delve deep into security measures, including password hashing, to ensure that user data is stored safely and that sensitive information is never exposed.
  • Implement a user login system where users can securely log in using their credentials
  • Define routes and create controller functions to handle different types of incoming requests.
  • Create and manage user accounts in MongoDB.
  • Set up MongoDB Database with MongoDB Atlas.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 15

  • Step 1: Installation of Node JS

    If you are using a cloud development environment like Google Cloud Shell, you can skip this step.

    To use ExpressJS, we will first need to install some tools and modules. We will need to install a JavaScript Runtime called Node. This will allow us to run JavaScript on our machine. Go to this link to install Node into your machine.

    Then, select the installer for the machines operating system. It will install an executable installer for seamless installation.

    Go to your machines file directory to look for the executable file and run it. It should install Node.js and npm.

    Once you have opened the installer, follow the on-screen steps to safely install the file into your machine. Node will then install some packages for you to install dependencies for any JavaScript project you may have.

    You can check that Node.js and npm have been installed successfully by entering these commands in your terminal or command prompt. You should get the versions of node and npm.

    node -v
npm -v
  • Step 2: Project Workspace Setup

    Now, create a folder on your computer. Rename this folder to StackUp-BackEnd-ExpressJS-Part-II. This will be the root folder for the projects that we will be using. Using a code editor of your choice such as VS Code, open the folder that we just created.

    Open the terminal where the current working directory should be the root folder you have created (i.e. StackUp-BackEnd-ExpressJS-Part-II). We will create a new folder for our project. Enter the following command.

    mkdir login-app

    Next, we will want to change directory to our project folder, as such, enter the command

    cd login-app

    Once we are within our project directory, enter the following two lines of commands within the terminal.

    mkdir models public views
npm install bcrypt body-parser dotenv ejs express express-session mongoose

    The first command will create 3 folders, models, public, and views within the project directory. The second command will install 7 packages into our project. These are the essential dependencies we need when creating our application.

    Previously, we used the body-parser package to allow us to read and parse our incoming request into a JSON object to be used within our application. We also used dotenv to store important and crucial environment variables within our projects. The ejs package, (Embedded JavaScript) is our view engine for rendering templates in our applications. Lastly we also learnt to use mongoose which is the Object Relational Mapping (ORM) tool to communicate with our database.

    We will be adding a new package and that is express-session, which is a session storage solution to track the users and their associate credentials as they interact with the application.

  • Step 3: Environment Variables

    Next, within the project folder, login-app, create a new file called .env. This file will be where we can store sensitive information like API Keys, Application Secrets, Database connections and more. It is a recommended practice for developers to adhere to this convention as .env files are usually used on a local level. Though the credentials and information are stored in plain text, usually .env files will be ignored by Git and will not be stored in a version source control service (VCS) like GitHub or GitLab. This reduces the risk of you having sensitive information uploaded onto a public GitHub repository.

    Now, copy the code below and add it to the .env file.

    db_connection="to_be_added_in_subsequent_steps"
PORT=3001
SESSION_SECRET='topsecret'
    Plain text

    In the code above, we have defined our port number to be 3001. Port numbers can be any number within the range of 1 to 65535. Only one application can use a specific port at any point in time. As long as the port is free, your NodeJS application is able to use it and listen for any incoming requests. However, there are some restrictions and conventions you will need to adhere to. Just to name a few, ports 80 and 443 are reserved for HTTP requests, port 22 is for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections and port 21 is for File Transfer Protocol (FTP). If you are interested in learning more about the various port reservations, you may read more about it here.

    We will be using the .env file to store our application port number, our Database connection string and secret. You can think of this file as an Environment Configuration. In Software Development, when deploying our applications to servers, sometimes our application might change different variables that run the application, like different database credentials, port numbers and more. .env files will be applied locally on the device where the file is placed. The secret in line 3 is used for encrypting the session.

    Next, you might be wondering how we are going to use these variables in our JavaScript files. In Step 2, we installed a package called dotenv. It is a JavaScript package that will do the necessary heavy lifting in managing and storing these variables, making it accessible to us in the JavaScript files. In subsequent steps, do look out for the import statements.

    require('dotenv').config();



const server = app.listen(process.env.PORT, () => {
  console.log("Server listening");
  mongoose.connect(process.env.db_connection).then(() => {
    console.log("Database Connected");
  });
});
    Plain text

    The code above is a sample usage of how we can use the environment variables. Firstly, we will need to import the dotenv package and once we are done with that, we will be able to access these variables by using process.env.name of variable. The name of the variable is case-sensitive, and it will be the same as the variables in the .env file.

  • Step 6: UserModel.js

    From what you might have learn from the previous campaign, we will create a new file within the models folder called UserModel.js which is a file that contains the Database Schema needed to interact with the models in MongoDB.

    Within the newly created file, UserModel.js, add the code below. 

    const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  username: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  },
  password: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  }
});

module.exports = mongoose.model('User', userSchema);
    JavaScript

    From here, we will create a new schema with 2 required entities, username (line 4) and password (line 8). In this file, we can also do data validation to set the entities as required (lines 6 and 10). You can think of this as the last line of defence when creating a new document (database object) in MongoDB.

    The schema will look at the entities needed to create a new document. If the object does not have the required entity, the Database will issue a fatal error, preventing an document to be created.

    Lastly, we can also tell by looking at the last line for which is the database model we are creating a new document for. In this case, we are creating a new document in the User Model with the userSchema. 

  • Step 7: app.js

    Now, we are ready to create our server script. We need to create an entry file which all requests will go through. Each request is also known as a route.

    The entry file will need to fulfil a few objectives:

    • Defining and using the Middlewares
    • Initializing the server
    • Handle the routings

    In your project folder, login-app, create a new file app.js. Open the file in your code editor and add the following code as provided below. 

    require('dotenv').config();
const express = require('express');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const session = require('express-session');
const bcrypt = require('bcrypt');
const User = require('./models/UserModel');

const app = express();
const port = process.env.PORT || 3001;

mongoose.connect(process.env.db_connection, {
    useNewUrlParser: true,
    useUnifiedTopology: true,
});

app.set('view engine', 'ejs');
app.use(express.static('public'));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

app.use(session({
    secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET,
    resave: false,
    saveUninitialized: false
}));

// Routes
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.render('welcome');
});

app.get('/register', (req, res) => {
    res.render('register');
});

app.post('/register', async (req, res) => {
    const { username, password } = req.body;
    const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10);

    const user = new User({
        username,
        password: hashedPassword
    });

    await user.save();

    res.redirect('/login');
});

app.get('/login', (req, res) => {
    res.render('login');
});

app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
    const { username, password } = req.body;

    const user = await User.findOne({ username });

    if (user && await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password)) {
        req.session.userId = user._id;
        req.session.username = user.username;

        return res.redirect('/dashboard');
    }

    res.redirect('/login');
});

app.get('/dashboard', (req, res) => {
    if (!req.session.userId) {
        return res.redirect('/login');
    }
    res.render('dashboard', {
        username: req.session.username
    })
});

const server = app.listen(port, () => {
    console.log("Server listening");
    mongoose.connect(process.env.db_connection).then(() => {
        console.log("Database Connected");
    });
});
    JavaScript

    This is essentially the basic code needed to get your server running. Like all code files, we will import all the modules we need at the start of the file.

    In the code, we start by importing the necessary modules. We use the express module to create an Express app. It is the basic framework and module we use while creating a Back End Application.

    Moving on, we create an instance of the Express app using the express() function in line 8. Additionally, we define a constant named port in line 9, which is set to 3000 by default. The server will use port 3000 if there is no .env file. This port value signifies the network port where our server will listen for incoming requests.

    In lines 11 to line 14, we will be connecting to mongoDB using Mongoose by specifying the connection string we added to the .env file earlier. As we proceed, we set up middleware functions for the Express app. In line 16, we will authorise ejs to be the view engine for rendering to the Front End. We will also define the static folder by pointing to our public folder we created earlier. The files within this folder should be cleared to be shown to the public and should not contain any other information sensitive to the users.

    We then configure our session and add it to our Express application (lines 20 to 24). In particular, the secret for encrypting the session is fetched from the environment variable SESSION_SECRET.

    Defining routes is an essential part of any web application. This section begins by defining the various routes or URLs that the application will respond to. For instance, when a user visits the root URL ("/"), it renders a "welcome" template (line 28) and when they go to "/register," it shows the "register" template (line 32).

    When a user submits a registration form (via HTTP POST to "/register"), it extracts the provided username and password from the body in line 36. The password is securely hashed using the bcrypt package we installed earlier, and a new user object is created with this hashed password. This user is then saved in a database in MongoDB using mongoose (line 44).

    When a user tries to log in (via HTTP POST to "/login"), the back end will check if the entered username exists in the database (line 56). If the username exists, it compares the provided password with the hashed password stored in the database line 58. If the passwords match, the user's session is initialized with their user ID and username using express-session (lines 59 and 60). Lastly, they are redirected to the "/dashboard." In line 62.

    To access the "/dashboard,", the code checks if the user has an active session by verifying the presence of a user ID. If not, it redirects them to the login page (line 70). If there's an active session, the "dashboard" template is rendered, showing the user's username (line 73).

    Finally, the code sets up a server to listen on a specified port and establishes a connection (line 77) to a database (MongoDB) using the provided database connection string. When the server starts, it logs messages to indicate that the server is listening and the database is connected (line 78 and line 80)

  • Step 9: Dashboard.ejs

    In this step, we will be creating the file to display the dashboard page to the user. This is the same file that will be rendered when a user have logged into the system. Within the views folder, create a new file called dashboard.ejs and add the following code below. 

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css">
    <title>Dashboard</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Hello, <%= username %>, Welcome to your Dashboard!</h1>
        <p>You are logged in.</p>
        <a href="/">Logout</a>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
    HTML

    Line 6 will make a link reference to the styles.css file we created in the previous step. We will also display the users username in line 11 by using the <%= %> ejs tags. Using this tag, we can output the JavaScript variable to the front end. 

  • Step 10: Login.ejs

    We will now create the file to be rendered to the user when they log in. Within the views folder, create a new file called login.ejs and add the following code below.

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css">
    <title>Login</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Login</h1>
        <form action="/login" method="POST">
            <label for="username">Username</label>
            <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required>
            
            <label for="password">Password</label>
            <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required>
            
            <button type="submit">Login</button>
        </form>
        <p>Don't have an account? <a href="/register">Register here</a>.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
    HTML

    There will be a <form> element (line 12) to allow users to enter their username and password. Once the user presses the submit button in line 19, the <form> element will make a HTML request to our back end to login. If the user registers instead, they can be redirected to the /register page (line 21).

    You should then see an output of "Server listening. Database Connected". 

    We have just created our very own login application server with ExpressJS using NodeJS. For users who completed the code locally (i.e. not using a cloud development environment), in your internet browser, enter this URL: http://localhost:3001.

    For users of Google Cloud Shell, at the top bar, click on the icon for web preview. Ensure the port number is 3001. Also, be sure to check the next step on instructions on how to ensure your cloud environment can connect to the database.

    Your browser should show the following output.

    This is working because as we enter the URL, http://localhost:3001, our browser will make a GET request to our server and right after, our server will respond to the get request (line 27 of app.js) and return with the following resources.

    In web development, "localhost" means your own computer. It's like your computer's nickname on the internet. You can also use a special number called an IP address, which is "127.0.0.1," along with a port number. This combination, like "127.0.0.1:<port number>," is also called an address.

    When working on your project, you use this address. But when ready to show your website to the world, you need to buy a special name for it, like "google.com" or "youtube.com." These names are called domains, and they're how people find your site on the internet.

  • Step 14: Troubleshooting Database Connections (Optional) 
    MongooseServerSelectionError: Could not connect to any servers in your MongoDB Atlas cluster. One common reason is that you're trying to access the database from an IP that isn't whitelisted. Make sure your current IP address is on your Atlas cluster's IP whitelist: https://www.mongodb.com/docs/atlas/security-whitelist/

    Sometimes, you will not be able to connect to the database. This is because MongoDB will whitelist the IP Address that was used to create the database. As such, only the connection from that IP Address can be connected to the database.

    To whitelist your new IP Address, open up MongoDB Atlas Dashboard and select the Network Access that is shown on the side navigation panel.

    Click on the Add IP Address button. You will then need to enter your IP address in the Access List Entry field. Then, click on Confirm. You should then see your IP address added to the IP Access List. Restart your application and try connecting again.

    In the event that you are using a cloud development environment like Codespaces, Gitpod or Google Cloud Shell, you may want to use the Allow Access from Anywhere . This will allow anyone using the same db_connection string, from the .env file, to access the database.

    Error: listen EADDRINUSE: address already in use :::3001

    Head to your .env, and change the port number to another number that is not in use.

    MongooseError: The `uri` parameter to `openUri()` must be a string, got "undefined". Make sure the first parameter to `mongoose.connect()` or `mongoose.createConnection()` is a string. 

MongoAPIError: URI must include hostname, domain name, and tld

    Check your .env file and ensure that the first line is correct. You have replaced your password correctly, and that the value is enclosed in " ". The password also does not have any special characters. 

    MongoServerError: bad auth : authentication failed

    Do check that the connection string that you are using in line 1 of .env is correct.
